// C3: Physical sensing components (data collector for CPS traces)
instance CPSDataCollector : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Collects raw data traces from the cyber‑physical system to feed the Digital Twin"
    DTDFVocab:producedData CollectedDataTrace
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction (raw data transmission)
instance CollectedDataTrace : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom CPSDataCollector
]

// C10: Data (raw trace)
instance RawCPSData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Raw data trace collected from the CPS, used as input for processing models"
    DTDFVocab:fromData CollectedDataTrace
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ProcessingEngine
]

// C10: Models (multiple abstraction layers)
instance SysMLStructureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "SysML block & internal‑block diagrams describing structure, properties and behavior"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ProcessingEngine
]

instance ACMEArchitectureModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "ACME ADL representation of component‑connector architecture for the Twin"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ProcessingEngine
]

instance SimulinkDynamicModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "White‑box Simulink dynamic simulation model used for analytical behavior prediction"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ProcessingEngine
]

instance MLPredictionModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Black‑box machine‑learning model (e.g., regression or neural network) for KPI prediction"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ProcessingEngine
]

// C11: Enabler (processing component)
instance ProcessingEngine : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Processing component that consumes input traces, executes associated simulation or data‑calculation models, and emits analytical output traces"
    DTDFVocab:enables KPIDecisionSupportService
]

// C6: Service (decision‑support)
instance KPIDecisionSupportService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Provides decision‑support by delivering predicted KPI values together with confidence scores; results can be visualized or sent to downstream control systems"
    DTDFVocab:provides PredictedKPIInsight, ConfidenceScoringInsight
]

// C17: Insights
instance PredictedKPIInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Predicted KPI values derived from processing of raw CPS data using simulation and ML models"
]

instance ConfidenceScoringInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Confidence scoring for each KPI prediction based on provenance and model metadata"
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle follows the MBSE development pipeline described in the documents: it starts with a requirements model, proceeds to functional‑architecture modeling, then logical‑architecture modeling, and finally a product/technical‑layer model. At the abstraction‑level stage a Digital‑Shadow Reference Model (UML class diagram) is instantiated; a concretization step maps reference concepts to concrete classes and associations, producing a conforming concrete model. After model concretization, processing components (data‑calculation or simulation models) are integrated, and the twin is deployed as an active component that consumes trace data and produces higher‑level outputs. Throughout the lifecycle, traceability links (originates‑from associations) preserve provenance across stages, supporting governance of model evolution."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity and validity are addressed through explicit traceability and verification of model transformations. The reliability of a digital shadow depends on the correctness of its underlying models and the transformations applied (e.g., from SysML specifications to simulation models such as Simulink). The reference model defines fine‑grained traceability, allowing each data trace to be traced back to its source models and processing components, thereby supporting verification of correctness. Validation methods include checking the consistency of model‑based transformations and ensuring that white‑box and black‑box model integration preserves predictive accuracy. Uncertainty and error sources are mitigated by maintaining the provenance chain of data traces and applying verification steps on model conversions."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The documents refer to the MQTT protocol (implemented by Mosquitto) as a communication layer for IoT data exchange (Ref [52]), and to the open‑source ThingsBoard platform (Ref [53]) as an IoT gateway that typically uses MQTT over TCP/IP. Thus the technical connection of the digital twin is based on an MQTT broker‑client architecture, transport over TCP/IP, and can be integrated into standard IP networks. No explicit bandwidth, latency, topology, or security specifications are provided in the documents."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The cited sources mention the ThingsBoard IoT platform (Ref [53]) and the Angular application framework (Ref [54]) as components that can be deployed on cloud, edge or on‑premise environments. ThingsBoard can run in containerised or virtual‑machine deployments, supporting scalability through its modular architecture, while Angular provides a web‑based UI. The documents do not detail concrete compute, storage, or SLA specifications, but indicate that the digital twin can be hosted using cloud‑oriented open‑source IoT middleware and web technologies."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The described Twin conforms to engineering standards captured in the documents: it uses SysML (including block diagrams and internal‑block diagrams) as the primary MBSE language, adopts ADLs (ACME, AADL, MontiArc) for component‑connector specifications, and is modelled as a UML class diagram reference model with an explicit conformance relation that maps concrete classes to reference concepts. The reference‑model approach follows the definition of a conformance relation as per the cited standard [41], ensuring interoperability and compliance with generic MBSE and model‑based simulation standards."
]